1192–Male":"1192–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1172–Female":"1172–Deceased","1190":"1190","Abt 1172":"about 1172","Abt 1200":"about 1200","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","1230":"1230","1172":"1172","Abt 1192":"about 1192","1192":"1192","Abt 1190":"about 1190",",, England":"England, United Kingdom","Of Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Patric","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from the personal name <i>Patrice</i>, Latin <i>Patricius</i> (see   Patrick  ). This surname is also found in the West Indies and Martinique.","Altered form of French   Patry  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Patrick","meanings":["Irish, Scottish, and English (of Norman origin): from the Anglo-Norman French, Middle English, and Older Scots personal name <i>Patrick</i> (Old Irish <i>Patraicc</i>), derived from Latin <i>Patricius</i> ‘son of a noble father, member of the patrician class’. This was the name of a Christian saint, a 5th-century Romano-Briton who became the apostle and patron saint of Ireland, and it was largely as a result of his fame that the personal name was so popular from the Middle Ages onward. In Ireland the surname is usually Scottish in origin, from Scottish settlers in Ulster in the 17th century. See also   Peden   and   McPadden  , derived from pet forms of Old Irish <i>Patraicc</i>.","Scottish and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Scottish and Irish Gaelic <b>Mac Phádraig</b> ‘son of Patrick’.","English: variant of   Partridge  ."]},{"name":"Patry","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Jean-Guy, Pierre, Benoit, Gaston, Gisele, Jean-Pierre, Julien, Luc, Lucien, Marcel, Michel.","French: from a vernacular form of the personal name   Patrice   (see   Patrick  ). Compare   Patrie  .","English and Scottish: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Patry</i>, a pet form of   Patrick   and (in Scotland)   Peter  . Compare Scottish   Petrie  , of which this was sometimes a variant. This name was formerly widespread, especially in western England and northeast Scotland, but is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Mrs.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Latin <i>Ursus</i> ‘bear’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Patric was born about 1172, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 3 sons with William Robert de Patrick."},"et":{"Abt 1172–":"umbes 1172–Surnud","1155–1200":"1155–1200","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1192–Male":"1192–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1190":"1190","Abt 1172":"umbes 1172","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","1230":"1230","1172":"1172","Abt 1192":"umbes 1192","1192":"1192","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190",",, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpa